name: unescapeJava
docstring:
/** *

Unescapes any Java literals found in the String. For example, it will turn a sequence of '\' and 'n' into a newline character, unless the '\' is preceded by another '\'.

* @param str the String to unescape, may be null * @return a new unescaped String, null if null string input */
human_label: Unescapes Java that found in the String.
one_line_summary: Convert Java escape sequences in a string to actual characters.
function_behavior: Transforms escape sequences (like \n, \t) in the input string to their respective characters, writing the result to a StringWriter.
examples:
"Hello\\nWorld" -> "Hello\nWorld" (newline converted)
"Tab\\tSeparated" -> "Tab\tSeparated" (tab converted)
"\\\\" -> "\\" (backslash preserved)
precond_postcond: Input string may have escape sequences and the output will have them converted to respective characters.
description: Unescapes Java that found in the String.
signature: public static String unescapeJava(String str) throws Exception {

name: resolveBound
human_label: Resolve the class of the first bound for the typeVariable recursively,return Unknown.class if it can't be resolved.Otherwise return the bound.
one_line_summary: Resolve type bounds for a TypeVariable.
function_behavior: This function resolves the first bound of a given type variable and recursively resolves it if it's another type variable. It returns Unknown.class if there are no bounds or if the bound is Object.class.
function_signature:
@param typeVariable TypeVariable<?>: the type variable to resolve the bound for
   @return Type: the resolved type bound
examples:
unboundedTypeVar -> Unknown.class (no bounds)
typeVarWithBound -> SomeClass.class (first non-object bound)
circularBound -> SomeClass.class (resolves recursively)
precond_postcond: TypeVariable must be non-null; returns a resolved bound or Unknown.class if unresolved.
description: Resolve the class of the first bound for the typeVariable recursively,return Unknown.class if it can't be resolved.Otherwise return the bound.

name: lastWriteTimeStampInMilliseconds
docstring:
/** 
 * The last time, in milliseconds, a write operation occurred.
 * @return this
 */
human_label: Check whether lastwrite is - 1. If yes, return - 1. Otherwise, return System.currentTimeMillis().
one_line_summary: Returns the last write timestamp or the current time if not set.
function_behavior: If lastWrite equals -1, it returns the current system time in milliseconds; otherwise, it returns lastWrite.
function_signature: @return long: The last write timestamp or current time in milliseconds.
examples:
lastWrite = -1 -> current time (lastWrite not set)
lastWrite = 1622538093000 -> 1622538093000 (returns lastWrite)
lastWrite = 0 -> 0 (returns lastWrite)
precond_postcond: lastWrite is an internal variable, initialized to -1 if unset; returns a valid long timestamp.
description: Check whether lastwrite is - 1. If yes, return - 1. Otherwise, return System.currentTimeMillis().

name: decodeOctets
docstring:
/**

 */
human_label: Decode octets to characters with UTF-8, append them to the given StringBuilder, and return the index to the next unchecked character.
one_line_summary: Decode and append bytes to a StringBuilder.
function_behavior: The function reads bytes from ByteBuffer, decodes them as a UTF-8 string, appends the result to StringBuilder, and returns an incremented index based on the byte sequence length.
examples:
1 byte with value < 0x80 -> index+2 (decoded single byte)
Multiple bytes -> index + bytes_count*3 - 1 (decoded multiple bytes)

name: decodePath
docstring:
/** 
 * Decode the path component of a URI as path segments.
 * @param u the URI. If the path component is an absolute path componentthen the leading '/' is ignored and is not considered a delimiator of a path segment.
 * @param decode true if the path segments of the path componentshould be in decoded form.
 * @return the list of path segments.
 */
human_label: Decode the raw path.
one_line_summary: Decodes URI paths based on given flag.
function_behavior: Processes and optionally decodes the path segments of a URI, removing any leading slash, and returns processed segments.
examples:
URI("/example/path", true)
-> List[pathSegment1, pathSegment2] (Decodes and splits path)
URI("/example/path", false)
-> List[pathSegment1, pathSegment2] (Splits path, no decoding)
URI("", true)
-> List[] (Empty path results in empty list)
precond_postcond: The input URI can be empty or with leading slash; the output is a list of path segments, optionally decoded.
description: Decode the raw path.
signature: public static List<PathSegmentImpl> decodePath(URI u,boolean decode){

name: encodeTemplateNames
docstring:
/** 
 * Encodes a string with template parameters names present, specifically the characters '{' and '}' will be percent-encoded.
 * @param s the string with zero or more template parameters names
 * @return the string with encoded template parameters names.
 */
human_label: Encoding the given string by changing '{' and '}' to the specified character for each,return the string after encoding.
one_line_summary: Replaces curly braces in a string with URL-encoded versions.
function_behavior: The function searches for '{' and '}' in the input string and replaces each occurrence with the encoded strings "%7B" and "%7D" respectively.
function_signature: @return String: The modified string with encoded curly braces.
examples:
"{hello}" -> "%7Bhello%7D" (both braces replaced)
"text" -> "text" (no braces so no change)
"a{b}c" -> "a%7Bb%7Dc" (braces encoded)
precond_postcond: The input is a non-null string. The output is the original string with encoded curly braces if any present.
description: Encoding the given string by changing '{' and '}' to the specified character for each,return the string after encoding.

Map<K,V> -> [K, V] (resolves Map type arguments)
T extends Number -> [Number] (resolves type variable)

description: Resolve and return the arguments for the genericType using the type variable information for the targetType. Returns null if  genericType is not parameterized or if arguments cannot be resolved.

name: capitalize
human_label: Converts a name of the string type to a character array and converts the first letter to an uppercase letter.
one_line_summary: Capitalizes the first character of a non-empty string.
function_behavior: Converts the first character of a given string to uppercase. Returns the modified string without altering other characters.
function_signature:
@param name String: The input string to be capitalized
   @return String: The string with the first character capitalized
examples:
"hello" -> "Hello" (capitalizes 'h')
"java" -> "Java" (capitalizes 'j')
"" -> "" (empty string remains unchanged)
null -> null (returns null for null input)
precond_postcond: Input is a string or null; output is the modified string with an uppercase first character or unchanged for empty/null input.
description: Converts a name of the string type to a character array and converts the first letter to an uppercase letter.

name: classPath
human_label: Creates an array of the file type based on all file names in java.class.path and returns the array.
one_line_summary: Converts the Java class path to an array of Files.
function_behavior: The function retrieves the Java class path, splits it into individual paths using the system path separator, and creates a File object for each path.
function_signature: @return File[]: Array of File objects representing Java class path entries.
examples:
java.class.path "lib1.jar:lib2.jar" -> [lib1.jar, lib2.jar] (Class paths converted to File array)
java.class.path "/path/to/lib1:/path/to/lib2" -> [/path/to/lib1, /path/to/lib2] (Absolute paths as File objects)
precond_postcond: System property "java.class.path" must be set, output is an array of File objects representing the paths.
description: Creates an array of the file type based on all file names in java.class.path and returns the array.

name: addReverse
human_label: Put the given array of files into a stack in reverse order.
one_line_summary: Iterates over an array of files in reverse order and pushes them onto a stack.
function_behavior: Checks if the input array is null. If not, iterates the array backward and adds each file to a stack.
function_signature: @param files File[]: Array of files to be added in reverse.
examples:
files = {file1, file2, file3} -> stack: {file3, file2, file1} (adds files in reverse)
files = {} -> stack: {} (no files added)
files = null -> no change (null array, returns immediately)
precond_postcond: Precondition: Input array may be null. Postcondition: Files are added to the stack in reverse order if the array is not null.
description: Put the given array of files into a stack in reverse order.

name: pop
docstring:
/** 
 * Pops the given number of abstract types from the output frame stack.
 * @param elements the number of abstract types that must be popped.
 */
human_label: Pop the given number of elements from the stack.
one_line_summary: Reduces output stack size by a specified number of elements.
function_behavior: Decreases `outputStackTop` by `elements` if possible; adjusts `outputStackStart` otherwise.
function_signature: @param elements int: Number of elements to pop from the stack.
examples:
elements=5, outputStackTop=10 -> outputStackTop=5 (Reduced successfully)
elements=5, outputStackTop=2 -> outputStackTop=0, outputStackStart-3 (Adjusted start)
precond_postcond: Assumes `outputStackTop` and `outputStackStart` are initialized and valid, resulting in decreased stack size.
description: Pop the given number of elements from the stack.

name: nextPrime
docstring: /** * Returns a prime number which is >= desiredCapacity and very close to desiredCapacity (within 11% if desiredCapacity >= 1000). * @param desiredCapacity the capacity desired by the user. * @return the capacity which should be used for a hashtable. */
human_label: Returns the element at the location specified by desiredCapacity in primeCapacities.
one_line_summary: Finds the smallest prime greater than or equal to a given number.
function_behavior: If the desired capacity is larger than or equal to the largest known prime, it returns the largest prime. Otherwise, it returns the next prime from a pre-sorted array.
function_signature:
@param desiredCapacity int: capacity for which to find the next prime.
   @return int: the next prime capacity.
examples:
10 -> 11 (10 < 11, next prime)
17 -> 17 (exact match)
100 -> 101 (next prime after 100)
precond_postcond: Input is a non-negative integer; output is the smallest prime greater than or equal to the input.
description: Returns the element at the location specified by desiredCapacity in primeCapacities.

name: enlarge
docstring:
/** 
 * Enlarges this byte vector so that it can receive 'size' more bytes.

 */
human_label: Convert the original data array to a longer array.

examples:
size=5 with data.length=10, length=8 -> enlarges data (fits 13 elements)
size=20 with data.length=15, length=12 -> enlarges data (fits 32 elements)
size=0 with data.length=20, length=18 -> keeps data (no size change needed)

name: pop
docstring:
/** 
 * Pops an abstract type from the output frame stack and returns its value.

 */
human_label: Pop an abstract type from the output frame stack and return its value.

(outputStackTop=2, outputStack={5,3})

description: Pop an abstract type from the output frame stack and return its value.

name: pop
docstring:

human_label: Pop different value of type based on the first character of the given descriptor.

"(I)
V" -> pop((Type.getArgumentsAndReturnSizes("(I)
V") >> 2) - 1) (method descriptor)
"J" -> pop(2)
(long type)
"L" -> pop(1)
(other types)
precond_postcond: Preconditions: Valid Java type descriptor is provided. Postconditions: Stack is adjusted according to the descriptor's needs.
description: Pop different value of type based on the first character of the given descriptor.

name: buildContentRange

name: removeFromTreeEdgeList

name: edgeToNext

name: isClique
docstring: /** * Check whether the subgraph of graph induced by the given vertices is complete, i.e. a clique. * @param graph the graph. * @param vertices the vertices to induce the subgraph from. * @return true if the induced subgraph is a clique. */
human_label: Return true if the subgraph of the given graph induced by the given vertices is a clique,otherwise return false.
one_line_summary: Checks if given vertices form a clique in a graph.
function_behavior: The function iterates through all pairs of vertices and returns false if any pair is not connected by an edge; otherwise, returns true.

(vertices={A,B,C}, edges={AB, AC, BC})
-> true (All pairs are connected)
(vertices={A,B,C}, edges={AB})
-> false (C is not connected to A or B)
(vertices={A,B}, edges={AB})
-> true (A and B are connected)
precond_postcond: Assumes no self-loops in the graph; returns true if all vertex pairs have edges.
description: Return true if the subgraph of the given graph induced by the given vertices is a clique,otherwise return false.

name: identity

name: computeGlobalSeparatorList
docstring:

 * @return the list of minimal separators of every edge $e$ in the inspected graph

description: Select an edge which isn't a circle in the graph,compute the list of the minimal separators in the neighborhood of the edge and put the pair of list and edge into the return list.Repeat for each edge in the graph and then return the final list.

name: compressTimeBucket
human_label: Follow the dayStep to reformat the time bucket with TIME_BUCKET_FORMATTER. For example, if dayStep == 11, 20000105 re-formatted time bucket is 20000101, 20000115 re-formatted time bucket is 20000112, 20000123 re-formatted time bucket is 20000123.
one_line_summary: Adjusts the given time bucket to align with a specified day step.
function_behavior: The function calculates a new time bucket by adjusting the input bucket back to the nearest multiple of the given day step. It returns the original bucket if the day step is 1.
examples:
20230101, 2 -> 20230101 (original value returned)
20230102, 2 -> 20230101 (adjusted to previous day step)
20230110, 3 -> 20230109 (adjusted by day step)
precond_postcond: Input must be a valid time representation; output is a valid time bucket aligned to the nearest day step.
description: Follow the dayStep to reformat the time bucket with TIME_BUCKET_FORMATTER. For example, if dayStep == 11, 20000105 re-formatted time bucket is 20000101, 20000115 re-formatted time bucket is 20000112, 20000123 re-formatted time bucket is 20000123.

name: init
human_label: Initializes a directory.
one_line_summary: Initializes a directory for analysis results.
function_behavior: Creates the directory if it doesn't exist; throws an exception if the path is a file.
function_signature: @throws IllegalArgumentException: If analyzeResultDist is a file instead of a directory.
examples:
nonexistent_path -> creates directory (creates directory)
existent_directory_path -> does nothing (directory exists, no action)
existent_file_path -> throws IllegalArgumentException (path is a file)
precond_postcond: Path must either not exist or be a directory; postcondition is a ready-to-use directory or an exception if invalid.
description: Initializes a directory.

name: isExpired
docstring:
/** 
 * @param timestamp        of current time
 * @param expiredThreshold represents the duration between last update time and the time point removing from cache.
 * @return true means this metrics should be removed from cache.
 */
human_label: Return true if the timestamp minus the lastUpdateTimestamp is greater than expiredThreshold,otherwise return false.
one_line_summary: Checks if a timestamp is beyond an expiration threshold.
function_behavior: Returns true if the difference between `timestamp` and `lastUpdateTimestamp` exceeds `expiredThreshold`.
examples:
1000, 500 -> true (Expired)
1000, 600 -> false (Not expired)
1500, 400 -> true (Expired)
precond_postcond: Assumes `lastUpdateTimestamp` is initialized; returns true if expired, false otherwise.
description: Return true if the timestamp minus the lastUpdateTimestamp is greater than expiredThreshold,otherwise return false.

name: addNewTarget
human_label: Add the given target channels to the consumeTargets.
one_line_summary: Adds a new target to the existing list of consume targets.
function_behavior: Creates a new Group object using provided channels and consumer, adds it to a list, and updates consumeTargets.
function_signature:
@param channels Channels: Channels instance for group.
   @param consumer IConsumer: Consumer instance for group.
examples:
addNewTarget(ch1, cons1)
-> adds group to consumeTargets (adds ch1, cons1 to list)
precond_postcond: List of consumeTargets must be iterable, increased by one Group object after the function executes.
description: Add the given target channels to the consumeTargets.

name: overrideName
human_label: Change the elements whose values are oldName to newName in column
one_line_summary: Replaces old column names with new ones in an array.
function_behavior: Iterates over the columns array, replacing occurrences of oldName with newName.
function_signature:
@param oldName String: Existing column name to be replaced
   @param newName String: New column name to set
examples:
["A", "B", "C"], "B", "D" -> ["A", "D", "C"] (B replaced with D)
["A", "A", "A"], "A", "Z" -> ["Z", "Z", "Z"] (All A's replaced with Z)
["X", "Y"], "Z", "W" -> ["X", "Y"] (No change as Z not found)
precond_postcond: Assumes columns is a non-null array of strings. After execution, columns will have all instances of oldName replaced with newName.
description: Change the elements whose values are oldName to newName in column

name: valueAccumulation
human_label: Add the value to the original value of the key.
one_line_summary: Accumulates values in a map based on a key.
function_behavior: Adds a Long value to the existing value for a given key in the data map. If the key doesn't exist, it initializes it with the given value.
function_signature:
@param key String: the key for accumulating value in the map
   @param value Long: the value to add to the existing value in the map
examples:
"a", 5L -> updates "a" with 5 (key "a" is initialized to 5)
"a", 3L -> updates "a" with 8 (key "a" sum is updated to 8 if already was 5)
"b", 2L -> updates "b" with 2 (key "b" is initialized to 2)
precond_postcond: The data map must be initialized; after execution, the key will have an updated accumulated value.
description: Add the value to the original value of the key.

name: id
human_label: Return the id by concatenating the point and the entity id with id connector.
one_line_summary: Joins a point with entityId using a connector or returns the point.
function_behavior: Returns a string combining point and entityId with a connector if entityId is not null; otherwise, returns point.
function_signature: @return String: Resulting concatenated or solo string based on the input.
examples:
null -> "point_value" (returns point)
"123" -> "point_value-CONNECTOR-123" (combines point and entityId)
"" -> "point_value-CONNECTOR-" (combines point and empty entityId)
precond_postcond: entityId may be null; output will have the structure point or point-CONNECTOR-entityId.
description: Return the id by concatenating the point and the entity id with id connector.

name: buildTimeRanges
human_label: Split time ranges to insure the start time and end time is small than FETCH_DATA_DURATION.
one_line_summary: Splits a time range into smaller ranges based on a constant duration.
function_behavior: Divides a start-to-end time range into smaller ranges each with a maximum duration defined by FETCH_DATA_DURATION, returning a list of these ranges.
examples:
100, 200 -> [TimeRange(100, 160)
, TimeRange(160, 201)
] (time ranges split by FETCH_DATA_DURATION)
150, 150 -> null (start equals end, returns null)
80, 60 -> null (invalid range, start greater than end)
precond_postcond: The start must be less than end to return a valid list, otherwise returns null. The list consists of TimeRanges each with a duration up to FETCH_DATA_DURATION.
description: Split time ranges to insure the start time and end time is small than FETCH_DATA_DURATION.

name: buildContent
human_label: Put the "content" from the  jsonObject to the content.
one_line_summary: Constructs a content map from a JSON object.
function_behavior: The function extracts "msg_type" and a modified "content" from a JsonObject, adding <at> tags for user IDs found in the "ats" field.
function_signature:
@param jsonObject JsonObject: The input JSON object containing the required fields.
   @return Map<String,Object>: A map with keys "msg_type" and "content".
precond_postcond: Assumes valid JsonObject input and modifies the "content" field with user ID mentions if "ats" is present.
description: Put the "content" from the  jsonObject to the content.

name: convertProperties
human_label: Convert process properties to the JsonObject.
one_line_summary: Converts a list of key-value pairs to a JsonObject.
function_behavior: The function iterates over a list of KeyStringValuePair objects and adds each key-value pair as a property in a new JsonObject. The resulting JsonObject contains all the key-value pairs from the input list.
function_signature:
@param properties List<KeyStringValuePair>: List containing key-value pairs to be converted.
   @return JsonObject: JsonObject containing the converted properties.
examples:
[{"key":"name","value":"John"}] -> {"name":"John"} (single pair conversion)
[{"key":"age","value":"25"}, {"key":"country","value":"USA"}] -> {"age":"25","country":"USA"} (multiple pairs conversion)
[] -> {} (empty list to empty JsonObject)
precond_postcond: Properties list should not contain null keys; result JsonObject will have all input key-value pairs.
description: Convert process properties to the JsonObject.

name: accept
docstring:
/** 
 * Accept the data into the cache and merge with the existing value. This method is not thread safe, should avoid concurrency calling.
 * @param data to be added potentially.
 */
human_label: Accept the data into the buffer if its id does not exist in the buffer. Otherwise try to combine it with the existing value, and remove it if the combined is abandoned.
one_line_summary: Update or remove METRICS data in a buffer.
function_behavior: The function checks if METRICS data already exists in the buffer, adds it if not, or combines it if it does; it removes the data if it's flagged as abandoned.
function_signature: @param data METRICS: The METRICS object to be processed.
examples:
new data -> buffer updated (Data added when new)
repeat data, not combined -> buffer unchanged (Data exists and combined)
repeat data, combined, abandoned -> buffer updated (Data removed when abandoned)
precond_postcond: Assumes `data` implements `combine` method and `buffer` supports put, get, remove operations, ensures buffer consistently represents current METRICS state.
description: Accept the data into the buffer if its id does not exist in the buffer. Otherwise try to combine it with the existing value, and remove it if the combined is abandoned.

name: isCompatible
human_label: Check whether the existed buckets are the same as the buckets.
one_line_summary: Checks compatibility of dataset buckets with predefined buckets.
function_behavior: Compares sorted keys from the dataset to predefined bucket values after processing. Returns true if both arrays of buckets match.
function_signature: @return boolean: True if dataset buckets match predefined buckets, false otherwise.
examples:
dataset with sortedKeys ["INFINITE_NEGATIVE", "1"] and buckets [Long.MIN_VALUE, 1] -> true (buckets match)
| dataset with sortedKeys ["INFINITE_NEGATIVE", "2"] and buckets [Long.MIN_VALUE, 1] -> false (buckets do not match)
| dataset with sortedKeys ["0:1", "2"] and buckets [1, 2] -> true (buckets match)
precond_postcond: Dataset keys must be parseable integers after last colon; output is false if arrays differ in length or content.
description: Check whether the existed buckets are the same as the buckets.
